irst Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":10,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Battisford was born about 1372, in Bexhill, Sussex, England, her father, Sir William Batisford of Wartling, was 42 and her mother, Lady Margaret de Peplesham, was 38. She married Sir William II Echyngham before 1395. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died after 1398, in Etchingham, Sussex, England."},"et":{"about 1372–after 1398":"umbes 1372–pärast 1398","1364–1406":"1364–1406","1366–1453":"1366–1453","1372–1398":"1372–1398","1374–1439":"1374–1439","1350–1413":"1350–1413","1394–1464":"1394–1464","1396–1473":"1396–1473","1331–1404":"1331–1404","1335–1405":"1335–1405","1363":"1363","1473":"1473","1396":"1396","1374":"1374","1394":"1394","1350":"1350","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","bef.